<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,152,538]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gonophores fixed sporosacs or free medusae, arising from hydranths or from gonostyles. Medusae, when present, with bell-shaped umbrella having an apical projection. Manubrium cruciform in cross-section; mouth with four prominent lips; radial canals jagged, four or more; mesenteries present. Newly liberated medusae with two opposite marginal tentacles; older medusae with up to six; tentacle bulbs conical. Gonads on interradii of manubrium, forming eight adradial masses. Ocelli absent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,152,538]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,351,377]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks.</emphasis>
Diagnosis of the polyphyletic genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Fewkes, 1887" authorityName="Fewkes" authorityYear="1887" box="[768,1085,352,378]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[768,911,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hydrichthys</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fewkes, J. W." box="[920,1085,352,378]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="604 - 605" refId="ref55622" refString="Fewkes, J. W. (1887) A hydroid parasitic on a fish. Nature, 36, 604 - 605." type="journal article" year="1887">Fewkes, 1887</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as given here follows that in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bouillon, J. &amp; Gravili, C. &amp; Pages, F. &amp; Gili, J. - M. &amp; Boero, F." box="[151,403,392,418]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="ref51270" refString="Bouillon, J., Gravili, C., Pages, F., Gili, J. - M. &amp; Boero, F. (2006) An introduction to Hydrozoa. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 194, 591 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Bouillon 
<emphasis box="[260,311,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert, P." box="[460,666,392,418]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="195 - 396" refId="ref64567" refString="Schuchert, P. (2007) The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera Part 2. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 114, 195 - 396." type="journal article" year="2007">Schuchert (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. Bouillon 
<emphasis box="[785,836,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al</emphasis>
. recognized seven species in this genus of parasitic hydroids, including 
<taxonomicName authority="Martin, 1975" authorityName="Martin" authorityYear="1975" box="[386,787,432,458]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pietschi">
<emphasis box="[386,628,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hydrichthys pietschi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martin, W. E." box="[635,787,432,458]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref60537" refString="Martin, W. E. (1975) Hydrichthys pietschi, new species, (Coelenterata) parasitic on the fish, Ceratias holboelli. Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences, 74, 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1975">Martin, 1975</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[859,948,432,458]" country="United States of America" name="Hawaii" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hawaii</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,152,538]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Hydroid species currently assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fewkes" authorityYear="1887" box="[665,808,472,497]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[665,808,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hydrichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known to liberate medusae referable to several genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert, P." box="[244,433,512,538]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="195 - 396" refId="ref64567" refString="Schuchert, P. (2007) The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera Part 2. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 114, 195 - 396." type="journal article" year="2007">Schuchert 2007</bibRefCitation>
), and the genus is in need of revision.
</paragraph>
